{"tipType":"windowShade","windowShade":{"windowShadeType":"framing","layout":"mediaLeft","initialOpenState":true,"content":"The goal of this activity is to have students use Hurricane Explorer to investigate the role of seasonal changes on hurricane formation and the effect of sea surface temperature on hurricane intensity. This activity begins by having students investigate the Saffir-Simpson Hurricane Wind scale and consider what might be responsible for different categories of storms. Students then investigate how sea surface temperature variations related to both seasonal changes and climate change play a role in hurricane intensity.

Students should be forming a systems view of hurricanes. By the end of the activity they should be able to reason about when and where they occur, how warm water fuels them, and what steers them. This is important as they consider how climate change may affect the intensity and frequency of hurricanes over time.  
","content2":"","mediaType":"none","mediaCaption":"Last, First. "Title of Work." Year created. Site Title [OR] Publisher. Gallery [OR] Location. http://www.url.com.","mediaURL":""}}

{"tipType":"questionWrapper","questionWrapper":{"correctExplanation":"","distractorsExplanation":"","exemplar":"<img src="https://has-resources.concord.org/resources/geohazard-hurricane/A3Q5snapshot.png" width="400">","teacherTip":"Hurricanes generally gain strength as they move over warmer temperature water and lose strength as they move over cooler water. 

For example, storms that move to the Caribbean and Gulf of Mexico tend to become very strong because the water temperature is higher in the shallower water.  

When storms hit cooler water or move over land, they tend to die out. Students should circle these areas on their screenshots.","teacherTipImageOverlay":"","location":"bottom"}}

{"tipType":"questionWrapper","questionWrapper":{"correctExplanation":"","distractorsExplanation":"","exemplar":"","teacherTip":"In recent history, it is clear that the sea surface temperature has risen. Historical temperature records are also suspect the farther back you go. The methods used to take the ocean's temperature one hundred years ago were highly inaccurate and unsophisticated in comparison to today in both the methods and tools used. 

Ocean temperature measurements from multiple sources over the past two centuries have recently been amassed and studied. The results have been shared with the scientific community. Additional work needs to be done in this area. For more information, see this article:

*<a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-019-02147-w" target="_blank">Corrections to ocean-temperature record resolve puzzling regional differences</a>*","teacherTipImageOverlay":"","location":"top"}}

{"tipType":"windowShade","windowShade":{"windowShadeType":"theoryAndBackground","layout":"mediaLeft","initialOpenState":true,"content":"**Why does a warmer climate result in more intense hurricanes?** 

First, it is important to know that warm air has the capacity to hold more moisture. With a rise in global temperature comes a rise in the evaporation of ocean water, which means lots of warm moist air. As low pressure systems travel over warmer oceans, moist air containing water vapor is pulled in. Warm water vapor condenses to form clouds releasing energy that fuels storms, intensifying the winds, and drawing even more moist air inward and upward. The more water in a storm, the more precipitation is released when a storm makes landfall. The result is an increase in higher category hurricanes that produce more rain and stronger winds. 

What risks do people and communities face as hurricanes become more intense? Simply stated, stronger hurricanes mean more damage and destruction from rain, flooding, and wind. The risk to human safety increases, and high costs for repairs, rebuilding, and mitigation follows.","content2":"","mediaType":"none","mediaCaption":"Last, First. "Title of Work." Year created. Site Title [OR] Publisher. Gallery [OR] Location. http://www.url.com.","mediaURL":""}}

{"tipType":"windowShade","windowShade":{"windowShadeType":"framing","layout":"mediaLeft","initialOpenState":true,"content":"The goal of this activity is to have students investigate factors that drive hurricane paths. **Students will develop an understanding about how high and low pressure systems drive the motion of hurricanes.** Students will use the Hurricane Explorer model to investigate how hurricanes are steered by global winds as hurricane movement is related to the wind fields in a system.  

Students will develop ideas about what is affecting a hurricane's movement by correlating tracks to modeled wind fields and by adjusting location and magnitudes of high and low pressure systems in the model to test their ideas. Once students learn about the role of pressure systems they will apply their understanding to comparing how real-world hurricanes that may have moved over similar spots ended up taking very different paths.
","content2":"","mediaType":"none","mediaCaption":"Last, First. "Title of Work." Year created. Site Title [OR] Publisher. Gallery [OR] Location. http://www.url.com.","mediaURL":""}}

{"tipType":"questionWrapper","questionWrapper":{"correctExplanation":"The storm makes landfall close to New York.","distractorsExplanation":"Boston is in Massachusetts, farther east and north than where the hurricane made landfall.

Philadelphia is in Pennsylvania, farther south and west than where the hurricane made landfall.

Baltimore is in Maryland, farther south and west than where the hurricane made landfall.","exemplar":"","teacherTip":"","teacherTipImageOverlay":"","location":"bottom"}}

{"tipType":"windowShade","windowShade":{"windowShadeType":"diggingDeeper","layout":"mediaCenter","initialOpenState":false,"content":"Looking for more resources on global winds? Check out this awesome **<a href="https://earth.nullschool.net/#current/wind/surface/level/orthographic=-40.71,22.40,386" target="_blank">Earth data visualization tool</a>**. 


If you are using this module during hurricane season, project this visualization in front of the classroom so that students can see how the winds move in real time. Zoom into the northern hemisphere to see how the winds in a low pressure system swirl in a counterclockwise direction and the winds in a high pressure system swirl clockwise.
","content2":"","mediaType":"none","mediaCaption":"Last, First. "Title of Work." Year created. Site Title [OR] Publisher. Gallery [OR] Location. http://www.url.com.","mediaURL":""}}

{"tipType":"questionWrapper","questionWrapper":{"correctExplanation":"As the hurricane goes by a high pressure system, it will be pushed away from the center of high pressure. High pressure systems have air flowing from higher in the atmosphere  to the surface of the earth. when this air hits the surface, it spreads out, and therefore pushes air away. Hurricanes are  influenced by these winds coming from high pressure systems and are steered around the high pressure systems.","distractorsExplanation":"Air flows out of a high pressure system. A storm cannot be drawn in when the air is pushing away.

The storm cannot travel straight through a high pressure system because the winds are blowing out of high pressure systems.

The winds flow out from the high pressure system, which means that the winds will affect the movement of storms.","exemplar":"","teacherTip":"Use the Teacher Dashboard to see what students are thinking.","teacherTipImageOverlay":"","location":"bottom"}}

{"tipType":"questionWrapper","questionWrapper":{"correctExplanation":"As a hurricane goes by a low pressure system, it will be drawn towards the low pressure system. The winds around low pressure systems flow inward, drawing storms toward Ls.","distractorsExplanation":"Because the winds flow towards low pressure (away from high pressure), storms cannot be pushed away. That is the opposite direction of wind flow.

Hurricanes cannot move straight through low pressure systems because the wind flow draws them inwards.

Similarly, hurricanes cannot be not affected by low pressure systems because of the winds.","exemplar":"","teacherTip":"Use the Teacher Dashboard to see what students are thinking.","teacherTipImageOverlay":"","location":"bottom"}}

{"tipType":"windowShade","windowShade":{"windowShadeType":"diggingDeeper","layout":"mediaLeft","initialOpenState":false,"content":"Scientists are currently researching the effect that increased greenhouse gas emissions may have on global wind shear. For many years, we have had a high level of vertical wind shear off the east coast of the United States, which has helped break up large storms like hurricanes as they approach the coast. If students have some background knowledge on atmospheric winds already, challenge them by showing them this graphic and webpage on recent research into climate change and wind shear. Ask, "How might the change in wind shear patterns affect the risk of a hurricane hitting the east coast of the United States?"

<a href="https://www.climate.gov/news-features/featured-images/warming-may-increase-risk-rapidly-intensifying-hurricanes-along-us" target="_blank">
Warming may increase risk of rapidly intensifying hurricanes along U.S. East Coast</a>","content2":"","mediaType":"image","mediaCaption":"NOAA","mediaURL":"https://has-production.s3.amazonaws.com/resources/geohazard-hurricane/hurricanes_globalwarming_VWSchange_large.png"}}

{"tipType":"windowShade","windowShade":{"windowShadeType":"discussionPoints","layout":"mediaLeft","initialOpenState":false,"content":"This is a good opportunity for students to come back after testing their predictions and discuss **the uncertainty in the models**, why their predictions may not have aligned with the test, and what changes they may make based on this test. Ideally, they will retest and reevaluate the outcome.

This is also a good place to return to the Summary Table and pull together what was learned abut pressure systems. How do pressure systems affect the path of the hurricane? Does pressure system location and magnitude help explain why hurricanes frequently hit some places and not others? 

Record student ideas on the Summary Table. (Please read these brief <a href="https://docs.google.com/document/d/1S-hG-ZKOmwEODJ0Q0HcsQ_sGH63JIL5sgq7MDDJiP9M/edit?usp=sharing" target="_blank">instructions on how to use Summary Tables</a>.)","content2":"","mediaType":"none","mediaCaption":"Last, First. "Title of Work." Year created. Site Title [OR] Publisher. Gallery [OR] Location. http://www.url.com.","mediaURL":""}}

{"tipType":"questionWrapper","questionWrapper":{"correctExplanation":"","distractorsExplanation":"","exemplar":"Hurricane hazards include flooding from storm surge, heavy rainfall, and high winds. Miami would be affected by all three.

Answers may vary but students may mention the following: Miami beach is a low-lying area. The buildings along the coast and the roads might be flooded either from storm surge or heavy rainfall. The wind could break windows, they buildings might lose power, the cars might be flooded and ruined, cares might be washed away, roads might be washed away, the parking lot might be washed away, trees might have their leaves stripped away by the wind. 
","teacherTip":"","teacherTipImageOverlay":"","location":"bottom"}}

{"tipType":"windowShade","windowShade":{"windowShadeType":"framing","layout":"mediaLeft","initialOpenState":true,"content":"When a hurricane approaches land, tremendous damage can be done to coastal cities and towns as well as to natural environments along the coast. The amount of damage a storm causes is dependent on the strength of a storm, the duration of the storm and where the storm hits. The goal of this activity is to have students use Hurricane Explorer to investigate the natural hazards that hurricanes bring including winds, rain, and storm surge, and the impact they have on the people and the environment in its path.

As students go through the activity it is important to emphasize that there is no way to stop a hurricane from hitting; however, with current technology and scientific understanding, people have a few days to prepare as a hurricane approaches.
","content2":"","mediaType":"none","mediaCaption":"Last, First. "Title of Work." Year created. Site Title [OR] Publisher. Gallery [OR] Location. http://www.url.com.","mediaURL":""}}

{"tipType":"questionWrapper","questionWrapper":{"correctExplanation":"","distractorsExplanation":"","exemplar":"The picture shows extreme damage. The houses sustained considerable damage, losing roofs and siding. It is unclear from the picture whether the homes were well-constructed, but there is other evidence to show extreme damage. Many of the trees appear to have been snapped by the wind, which is a component of the Extreme category. 

It is not clear that there are any power poles standing in the picture, but it seems like such a community would have had power poles in it before the storm. There is loose debris all over that could have caused additional destruction to the trees and houses.
","teacherTip":"","teacherTipImageOverlay":"","location":"bottom"}}

{"tipType":"questionWrapper","questionWrapper":{"correctExplanation":"The storm was Category 2 or Category 3 when it made landfall. This is shown by the yellowish-orange to orange color of the line. 

Zoom in to the model to see the exact point of landfall:

<img src="https://has-production.s3.amazonaws.com/resources/geohazard-hurricane/A4Q13Exemplar.png" width="400">","distractorsExplanation":"","exemplar":"","teacherTip":"","teacherTipImageOverlay":"","location":"bottom"}}

{"tipType":"questionWrapper","questionWrapper":{"correctExplanation":"","distractorsExplanation":"","exemplar":"This storm affected a lot of people at landfall. It hit a major US city, New York City, according to the population map overlay. Millions of people live in New York City and the surrounding area!

We do not expect students to submit a snapshot for this question. This is what they should be looking at, though.
<img src="https://has-production.s3.amazonaws.com/resources/geohazard-hurricane/A4Q16Exemplar.png" width="400">","teacherTip":"","teacherTipImageOverlay":"","location":"bottom"}}

{"tipType":"questionWrapper","questionWrapper":{"correctExplanation":"","distractorsExplanation":"","exemplar":"Answers will vary. Storm surge will impact communities on rivers closer to the ocean. So, if a student is in an area where there are no rivers, it is not likely people inland will be impacted by storm surge.

We do not expect students to submit a snapshot for this question. This is what they should be looking at, though.
<img src="https://has-production.s3.amazonaws.com/resources/geohazard-hurricane/A4Q17Exemplar.png" width="400">","teacherTip":"","teacherTipImageOverlay":"","location":"bottom"}}

{"tipType":"windowShade","windowShade":{"windowShadeType":"theoryAndBackground","layout":"mediaLeft","initialOpenState":true,"content":"**The challenge on this page is intended to pull together all that students have been learning in one place!** 

The Hurricane Explorer is set up so that the track of the modeled hurricane travels over the Mid-Atlantic region in the United States. Students will need to pull evidence from the maps and overlays and then make connections between the data about the hazards and the potential impacts of those hazards for the people living along the coast and inland. Each student will have a different response. 

What is most important on this page is how students reason about the combined hazards and impacts for a given region.","content2":"","mediaType":"none","mediaCaption":"Last, First. "Title of Work." Year created. Site Title [OR] Publisher. Gallery [OR] Location. http://www.url.com.","mediaURL":""}}

{"tipType":"questionWrapper","questionWrapper":{"correctExplanation":"","distractorsExplanation":"","exemplar":"","teacherTip":"Answers will vary. Students should have the Population map overlay on. 

They should be looking at something like this:
<img src="https://has-production.s3.amazonaws.com/resources/geohazard-hurricane/A4Q16Exemplar.png" width="400">","teacherTipImageOverlay":"","location":"bottom"}}

{"tipType":"questionWrapper","questionWrapper":{"correctExplanation":"","distractorsExplanation":"","exemplar":"I do think sea level will continue rise into the future. The trend in the graph has it increasing pretty steadily over time, and I don't think the trend is going to reverse in the coming years.","teacherTip":"If students are wondering how scientists measure sea level rise, show them this video:

**<a href="https://oceantoday.noaa.gov/sealevelsonthemove/welcome.html" target="_blank">Measuring Sea Level Rise</a>**
","teacherTipImageOverlay":"","location":"bottom"}}

{"tipType":"questionWrapper","questionWrapper":{"correctExplanation":"The temperature anomaly in 1880 was approximately -0.5°F. The temperature anomaly in 2015 was approximately 1.0°F. The difference between these readings is approximately 1.5°F.","distractorsExplanation":"The temperature is warmer in 2015 than in 1880, but a 5°F change is more than is shown on the graph. 

A zero degree change is not shown in the data, nor is a decrease in the temperature between 1880 and 2015.

","exemplar":"","teacherTip":"","teacherTipImageOverlay":"","location":"bottom"}}

{"tipType":"questionWrapper","questionWrapper":{"correctExplanation":"","distractorsExplanation":"","exemplar":"","teacherTip":"Student answers will vary.

This is a good spot to have students think aloud and share a justification for the choice they made. Specifically, push the students to draw on experiences from past activities to support the claim they are making regarding question 2. 
","teacherTipImageOverlay":"","location":"bottom"}}

{"tipType":"windowShade","windowShade":{"windowShadeType":"theoryAndBackground","layout":"mediaCenter","initialOpenState":false,"content":"A temperature anomaly is the difference in temperature compared to a baseline measurement. In this graph, the anomaly is the difference in sea surface temperature (SST) in each year compared to the overall average temperature between 1971 and 2000.  It is important to note that the SST carries across the globe. Precise measurements are taken at multiple sites located in each ocean. In each location, these measurements are compared to the baseline.  

For example, if the temperature measured in August 2019 in the Arctic was 4 degrees Celsius, and the average SST temperature in that location in August is 3 degrees Celsius, that is a +1 degree anomaly. Data from multiple sites are compiled to create graphs like this.

If students are wondering how scientists measure ocean temperatures, show them this video from NOAA.","content2":"","mediaType":"video","mediaCaption":"NOAA https://oceantoday.noaa.gov/takingtheoceanstemp","mediaURL":"https://has-production.s3.amazonaws.com/resources/geohazard-hurricane/otkn_211_takingtheoceanstemperature_lg.mp4"}}

{"tipType":"questionWrapper","questionWrapper":{"correctExplanation":"","distractorsExplanation":"","exemplar":"This is a big unknown. People like to live along the coast. So if they continue to live along the coast, they will be more affected by storms.

If, however, they do the sensible thing and move away from the areas of greatest hazard, then it's likely that the same number of people could be affected by hurricanes.
","teacherTip":"","teacherTipImageOverlay":"","location":"bottom"}}

{"tipType":"questionWrapper","questionWrapper":{"correctExplanation":"","distractorsExplanation":"","exemplar":"Wetlands can absorb some of the storm surge and winds. They provide a place where water can drain to during heavy rain instead of rapidly ponding like impermeable paved surfaces.

These types of wetlands would protect against storm surge. They absorb the water and act as a buffer against rising water being pushed onto the land. 

The wetlands also provide lots of area for runoff, so instead of water remaining in paved areas such as parking lots and streets, the water is absorbed into the wetlands and decreases the flooding faster than if it was not there.","teacherTip":"","teacherTipImageOverlay":"","location":"bottom"}}

{"tipType":"questionWrapper","questionWrapper":{"correctExplanation":"","distractorsExplanation":"","exemplar":"People can build in drainage basins for excess water to flow to rather than building houses in the lowest-lying areas. They can add buffer zones along streams to reduce the amount of flooding that affects structures. They can build seawalls that protect against some level of storm surge. They can add pumps to areas to pump out excess water as it accumulates.

They can install hurricane shutters to protect their windows and doors from flying debris. They can use sandbags to prevent flooding of their homes. 
","teacherTip":"","teacherTipImageOverlay":"","location":"bottom"}}

{"tipType":"questionWrapper","questionWrapper":{"correctExplanation":"","distractorsExplanation":"","exemplar":"Subway systems, by virtue of being underground, are prone to flooding. More flooding means that more water needs to be pumped out. 

Roads can be washed away by flooding. Roads should be constructed along areas that are less likely to flood (not along streams/rivers). 

Large buildings are affected by winds, but their foundations can flood or be washed away by storm surge. ","teacherTip":"","teacherTipImageOverlay":"","location":"bottom"}}

{"tipType":"windowShade","windowShade":{"windowShadeType":"teacherTip","layout":"mediaLeft","initialOpenState":true,"content":"Having completed the module, it is time to check in on the anchor question driving the unit.  Having students refer to their summary tables, as a class create a **Gotta Have** list of essential elements for an explanation or answer to the question How will hurricane risks and impacts change over the next 100 years?  

Provide time for the students to generate answers to the question (as individuals or as a group), share their explanations with others in a peer review format, and finally generate a whole class explanation. 
See <a href= "https://ambitiousscienceteaching.org/tools-face-to-face/#Gottahave" target="_blank">Gotta Have</a>.","content2":"","mediaType":"none","mediaCaption":"Last, First. "Title of Work." Year created. Site Title [OR] Publisher. Gallery [OR] Location. http://www.url.com.","mediaURL":""}}
